1. cs.CR (Cryptography and Security): The paper proposes a cryptographic protocol called DOMtegrity to ensure the end-to-end integrity of the DOM structure of a web page from delivering at a web server to the rendering of the page in the user's browser. The paper also discusses man-in-the-browser (MITB) attacks, which are a common topic in the cryptography and security subfield. 
2. cs.SE (Software Engineering): The paper discusses attacks on real-world online banking websites and proposes a solution to ensure the integrity of web content in the presence of malicious browser extensions. This involves software engineering techniques to modify the behavior of the browser and ensure the integrity of the DOM structure. 
3. cs.PL (Programming Languages): The paper discusses the differences between browser extensions and in-line JavaScript code and how these differences can be exploited to ensure the integrity of the DOM structure. This involves programming language concepts such as code execution and control flow.

This involves distributed computing concepts such as network communication and data transfer.
